class Solution {
public:
    int palindromePartition(string s, int k) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(n, 0));
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            dp[i][i] = 0;
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                if (s[i] == s[j]) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i + 1][j - 1];
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i + 1][j - 1] + 1;
                }
            }
        }
        int ans = INT_MAX;
        function<void(int, int)> dfs = [&](int l, int r) {
            if (r - l + 1 == k) {
                ans = min(ans, dp[l][r]);
                return;
            }
            for (int i = l; i <= r; i++) {
                if (i - l >= k - 1) {
                    dfs(l, i - 1);
                    dfs(i + 1, r);
                    return;
                }
            }
        };
        dfs(0, n - 1);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n^3)
space complexity: O(n^2)
energy implications: MEDIUM
explanation: This solution uses dynamic programming to build a 2D table dp where dp[i][j] represents the minimum number of changes needed to make the substring s[i..j] a palindrome. Then it uses a depth-first search (DFS) to try all possible ways to divide the string into k non-empty disjoint substrings. The DFS function tries to split the string at each position and recursively calls itself to divide the left and right parts. The minimum number of changes is updated at each step.

